   </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> <br />
Strategy:<br />
<br />
So I havent been real serious about Star Wars in a long time, but after a trip to Origins and Gencon this year, and seeing how the game is still alive and running, I decided to play in a few events. Unfortunately I was foolish enough to play Wars TCG this year, throwing away a good year and half for a game that blows! So Ive been getting back into Star Wars, playing a version similar of this deck at the Gencon consolation tournament. <br />
<br />
For any old school players out there, this is a Team-Albany Style Hunt Down that weve been running for ages!<br />
<br />
This deck plays like your generic docking bay Hunt Down. Search for sites, play sites, drop Vader, fight. At least that was how I played the deck until broken Mace, and Endor Mains came out. Dark side mains just cant keep up with light side mains, dont let anyone tell you other wise. Well, it can, you just need to find a way to get all those freaking Jedi lightsabers out of the way. Thats why I run three disarms and two premier Doctor Evazans. Disarm their Jedi, operate on those Jerks, and if youre lucky, use Darth Sidious to place them out of play. If you can get that off, youll gain board control, and force a fighting light side to find a new way to win. Often times it can not.<br />
<br />
At the Gencon consolation tournament I played three throne room mains decks. I went 2-1, losing to a bad draw. Hell when you play a mains deck it happens. It happens to throne room, and its a risk you run when you play it. As the famous bumper sicker says exhaust Happens.<br />
<br />
I changed the space package I ran at Gencon to the Guri / Xizor and Stinger / Virago package. The generic light side place package now is Bright Hope and Tantive IV. Youve got to come with over-powering density to knock that away. Thats what Ive focused my card choices on. Plus Xizor with Guri (V) is not a bad little duo to run on the ground.<br />
<br />
Another problem with HDADTJ was force. I think relying on Mpoints to pull your system for force is a waste. In todays environment half the decks are throne room and theyll just cancel you Mpoints first turn anyways. So I play the three 2/0s and four 2/0 pullers. Seven chances at a 2/0, thats better than most throne room decks force package. <br />
<br />
For card choices you could run four EPP Vaders, but there is nothing cooler that dropping Lord Vader and a lightsaber and saying This Site is MINE! Well, maybe not, broken Mace will come to say Hi, but its still cool none-the-less.<br />
<br />
I always like to start IAO & SP, Colo or Scando (Scando if they start Colo), and No Escape. I HATE HATE HATE having to search for No Escape when they get their Honor Out. HATE IT! You could fit in a YCHF, but it just preference.  <br />
<br />
Match-Ups<br />
Note: I am not going to pretend I am half the player I once was when I was World Champion in 2000, and tell you how you can win these match ups. Hell I havent played half these match-ups! But maybe I can give a little understanding to how I think you would win these games.<br />
Note: Props to Reid Smith, as half the math-ups listed are decks he designed. <br />
Note: Props to Drew Scott for having an enormous pair and playing Hunt Down for day 3 of worlds!<br />
Note: Props to Chris Twigg for always playing Hunt Down. I dont know the kids just cool and he play Albany style hunt down so well.<br />
Note: Screw it, props to All the Twiggs, King-Man, Art, Chu, Mikey D, and Jason Foss. <br />
<br />
For the match-ups listed, Ill listed the light side decks in the decktech top 10, as well as Throne room:<br />
<br />
Throne Room: For this game I like to play it slow. WHAT? I dont like to drop Vader and watch him get beat up. DRAW DRAW DRAW. Draw until you get Doctor Evazan and a disarm. Than go get back board control. Thats how I beat the two throne room decks. Theyll go for the Kessel drain, counter with Enter the Bureaucrat. Perhaps try to contest them with the multiply drawing destiny machines! Once you have board control with the disarm-tech, theyll be very hard pressed to try and come fight you back. When they do, youll have a better foot holding and more sustainable characters. I like to think youre a favorite in this match. <br />
<br />
Jesus Saves: Jared Lockwoods speeder deck: I think Jared maybe right on this one, its going to hard to win. The system is the key to the game here. Youre going to have to try and hold it. If you can somehow take the system from him, stop his retrieval, youll have a chance. Dont spend your time fighting at the fourth marker, ice storm will get you.     <br />
<br />
The Perfect MBO: David Destefanis MBO: I am not going to even try this one. Lets be honest, no one is the states plays this deck, and if he/she does, he/she is a scrub and youll will. If you want to play against a solid MBO, take a plane across the pacific, because you wont find one in the states. But props do go out to David, MBO is solid and can win, his deck list and its record is proof of that.<br />
<br />
Hidden BAMse: Alden Petersons hidden Base: Hidden base VS Hunt down match up. Search and Destroy and Visage will whack away the whole game. Remember those rebel wont escape us cancels targeting of Virago and Stinger. You can set up search and destroy fast, and flip second turn, so this game hidden base will be losing Four each full turn cycle. Thats not an easy thing to deal with.<br />
<br />
Let A Brother Play: Michael Richards Mains deck: Hes giving you three force first turn, and the decks got 16 characters. FIGHT FIGHT FIGHT! Youll out last him and the disarm tech will work greatly in your favor.          <br />
<br />
ReidTech inc. Presents Endor Mains: Reid Smiths Endor Mains deck: Hes giving you three force first turn. Youll have force activation up on this deck all game. But hes right, the deck has got mad tricks. I think if you can get some key guys with a killer disarm, you take control of the ground. A fight in space might be in your favor, if you can get the massive destiny draws going, you can take space. Its going to be a fight. I dont think his deck runs over mains; its a better game than given credit for.<br />
<br />
Thank Teh Meeker: Reid Smiths Agents deck: I have never played against or played an agents deck. I have heard of people saying HD is a good game against it, and Ive heard it gets blown away. I think the key to this game is the battles. Remember you take no battle damage when Guri is with Xizor. I wish I had some magic tech for this one, but I just dont know anything about Agents.<br />
<br />
Teh B0rk3n deck (concept): Reid Smiths Broken Deck: Like its says in his strategy, its a HD VS Throne room match up.   <br />
 <br />
Weird Random Decks: BY AARON KINGERY and others: Props to King-man for always playing weird exhaust. His Dagobah deck owns everything! But seriously, Visage and search and Destroy, what else do you need?<br />
<br />
Anyways, Hunt Down has its problems, but hell it won worlds this year! Hunt Down is always a good meti-choice when everyone is playing mains.<br />
<br />
Hope all is well with everyone is the Star Wars Universe!<br />
<br />
-Matthew Sokol<br />
2000 SWCCG World Champion<br />
2005 WARS TCG World Champion  frimbazel thats Lame..<br />
